<p>Scroll to the right to learn how a story flows through the system, from ideation to publishing</p>

<i class="fa fa-arrows-h fa-3x"></i>

<div class="timeline-window clearfix">
	<div class="timeline-wrapper clearfix">
	<div class="timeline-step" id="step-1">
<p class="label">STEP 1</p><br>

Editor-in-chief sets weekly story deadlines.
<em>Try to publish at least one article a day, so set deadlines accordingly.</em>
	</div>
	<div class="timeline-step">
<p class="label">STEP 2</p><br>
A writer pitches a story idea. Once it's approved by an editor, the writer immediately contacts their photographer to coordinate photos for the article.
	</div>
	<div class="timeline-step">
<p class="label">STEP 3</p><br>
Writer researches and writes the story and posts the story to WordPress. At the same time, the photographer uploads the photos to Flickr.
	</div>
	<div class="timeline-step">
<p class="label">STEP 4</p><br>
The writer takes the photos they want from Flickr and inserts them into their article.  Pick one to be the main photo.
	</div>
	<div class="timeline-step">
<p class="label">STEP 5</p><br>
The writer notifies the copyeditor that the story is ready to go, and the copyeditor edits for grammar, obvious mistakes and things that just don’t make sense.
	</div>
	<div class="timeline-step">
<p class="label">STEP 6</p><br>
The story moves on to the managing editor or editor-in-chief. They confirm that the story will be a hit, make necessary edits, and refine the title and subtitle to be killer. If the story has major issues, it’s sent back to the writer.
	</div>
	<div class="timeline-step">
<p class="label">STEP 7</p><br>
When the story looks good, the EIC publishes to the site and the writer promotes it on social media.
	</div>
</div>
</div>
<p class="small-caps">This process takes about a week and three days, usually.</p>

<p>*Throughout this process, the publishing spreadsheet will be updated.</p>
